ysed per week ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; width: 40%;\"\"\n!style=\"width: 5%;\"|Week\n!style=\"width: 10%;\"|New\n!style=\"width: 10%;\"|Total\n!style=\"width: 5%;\"|Sources(s)\n|-\n!1<!-- Started 9 March 2020 -->\n|59\n|59\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/MediaBulletin090320COVID19.pdf|title=MediaBulletin090320COVID19.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!2\n|37\n|96\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/MediaBulletin160320COVID19.pdf|title=MediaBulletin160320COVID19.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!3\n|416\n|512\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_23_03_20_%20COVID_19.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_23_03_20_%20COVID_19.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n!4\n|1408\n|1920\n|<ref name=\"30MarBulletin5pages\"/>\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" |{{Small|Numbers are deduced from daily reports provided by Health and Family Welfare Department.}}\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\u200e\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India by state or union territory|Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:2020s in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Health in Tamil Nadu]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of the viral pandemic in Tamil Nadu, India}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current event|2=current disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic]] in Tamil Nadu\n| width           = \n| map1            = TN COVID-19 cases in districts.svg\n| legend1         = Map of districts with confirmed cases (as of 30 March)\n{{legend|#d45500ff|30+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ff9955ff|10\u201329 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffe6d5ff|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| map4            = \n| legend4         = \n| map5            = \n| legend5         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]\n| first_case      = [[Chennai]]\n| arrival_date    = 7 March 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=07|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| confirmed_cases = 124<ref name=\"TNHFW\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/index.html|title=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu Stop Corona Home|website=stopcorona.tn.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n| active_cases    = 117<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n| suspected_cases = \n| recovery_cases  = 6<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n| deaths          = 1<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/>\n| territories     = 19 districts including [[Chennai district|Chennai]], [[Coimbatore district|Coimbatore]], [[Erode district|Erode]], [[Madurai district|Madurai]], [[Namakkal district|Namakkal]]\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{url|https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/}}\n| youtube         = \n}}\nThe first case of the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] in the Indian state of [[Tamil Nadu]] was confirmed on 7 March 2020. The state has confirmed a total of 124 cases, including 1 death and 6 recoveries, as of 31 March 2020.<ref name=\"TNHFW\"/><ref name=\"31MarBulletin2\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_31.03.2020_2_Pages_English_118_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health & Family Welfare Department - Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 April 2020}}</ref> 79 per cent of all reported cases till 31 March were from one cluster with more than 50 infections linked to a religious congregation event that took place in Delhi.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /> The state government has created containment zones in 12 affected districts to survey its residents for checking community spread and to prevent more infections.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n== Timeline ==\n\n=== March ===\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Tamil Nadu medical cases chart}}The first case of coronavirus was confirmed on 7 March in a resident from [[Kanchipuram]] in [[Chennai]]. He had returned from [[Oman]] and started developing symptoms including fever and cough.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-first-case-of-coronavirus-patient-quarantined-in-government-hospital-in-chennai/articleshow/74529929.cms?from=mdr|title=Tamil Nadu reports first case of Coronavirus; patient quarantined in Chennai Government Hospital|date=2020-03-09|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> He was isolated in [[Government General Hospital, Chennai|Rajiv Gandhi Government General Hospital]]. Later, on 10 March, he recovered and tested negative.<ref name=\"TNrecovered\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-no-fresh-covid-19-cases-in-tamil-nadu-812479.html?utm_campaign=fullarticle&utm_medium=referral&utm_source=inshorts|title=Coronavirus: No fresh COVID-19 cases in Tamil Nadu|date=10 March 2020|website=Deccan Herald|access-date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter more than a week without new cases, on 18 March, the second person who had travelled by train from [[Delhi]] to Chennai confirmed positive. He did not have any history of foreign travel and was described as a domestic case by the state health minister [[C. Vijayabaskar]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Tamil Nadu's 2nd Coronavirus patient raises community transmission fears|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadus-2nd-coronavirus-patient-raises-community-transmission-fears/articleshow/74702335.cms|newspaper=Economic Times|date=19 March 2020|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, a 21-year-old student who returned from [[Ireland]] tested positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/health/coronavirus-live-updates-total-covid-19-cases-in-india-death-toll-latest-news-global-market-crash-recession-120031900563_1.html|title=Coronavirus LIVE: India's death toll rises to four|website=Business Standard|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 March, a further three were confirmed positive - A Chennai man who had travelled from [[New Zealand]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/chennai/three-more-covid-19-cases-in-state-one-with-no-travel-history/article31146918.ece|title=Three more COVID-19 cases in State, one with no travel history|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-30|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> and two [[Thailand]] nationals in [[Erode]].<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-17-fresh-coronavirus-cases-tally-now-67-819262.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 17 fresh coronavirus cases; tally now 67|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> They were admitted to IRT Hospital in Perundurai in Erode. More than 300 people who had come in contact with the three patients were quarantined.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-reports-7th-positive-coronavirus-case-816543.html|title=Tamil Nadu reports 7th positive coronavirus case|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March, the first virus-related death in the state was reported after a 54-year-old man in [[Madurai]] died.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.patrikai.com/first-corona-death-in-tn-madurai-men-of-54-years-old-expired/|title=\u0bae\u0ba4\u0bc1\u0bb0\u0bc8\u0baf\u0bbf\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0ba4\u0bae\u0bbf\u0bb4\u0b95\u0ba4\u0bcd\u0ba4\u0bbf\u0ba9\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bc1\u0ba4\u0bb2\u0bcd \u0b95\u0bca\u0bb0\u0bcb\u0ba9\u0bbe \u0baa\u0bb2\u0bbf : 54 \u0bb5\u0baf\u0ba4\u0bc1 \u0ba8\u0baa\u0bb0\u0bcd \u0bae\u0bb0\u0ba3\u0bae\u0bcd {{!}} Patrikai - Tamil Daily - latest online local breaking news & reviews - Tamilnadu, India & World - politics, cinema, cricket, video & cartoon|date=2020-03-25|website=Tamil News patrikai {{!}} Tamil news online {{!}} latest tamil news|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-28}}</ref> Five others were infected - four Indonesians and their travel guide from Chennai.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://m.economictimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-reports-five-new-coronavirus-cases-tally-goes-up-to-23/articleshow/74810591.cms|title=Tamil Nadu reports five new coronavirus cases; tally goes up to 23|author=|newspaper=Economic Times|date = 26 March 2020}}</ref> The five were in quarantine since 22 March in Salem Medical College.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-reports-5-new-cases-covid-19-includes-4-indonesian-travellers-and-1-chennai-man-121103|title=TN reports 5 new cases of COVID-19, includes 4 Indonesian travellers and 1 Chennai man|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=The News Minute|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, a 21-year-old youth who had just returned from a trip to [[Dublin]], Ireland was discharged from the hospital.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://wap.business-standard.com/article/news-ani/covid-19-positive-tamil-nadu-man-with-travel-history-to-ireland-recovers-120032800122_1.html|title=Covid-19 positive Tamil Nadu man with travel history to Ireland recovers|author=|date=28 March 2020|newspaper=Business Standard India|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Two new cases - one each in [[Kumbakonam]] and [[Katpadi]] were reported. With this, the total number of confirmed cases had reached 40 in the state.<ref name=\"28Bulletin\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_28_03_2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March, the state reported eight more cases (four each from Coimbatore and Erode), all of which were linked to the two [[Thailand|Thai]] nationals and their group who had tested positive. The eight included a 10-month-old baby.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/10-month-old-baby-and-7-more-test-positive-for-covid-19-in-tamil-nadu-states-tally-rises-to-50-818967.html|title=10-month-old baby and 7 more test positive for COVID-19 in Tamil Nadu; state's tally rises to 50|date=29 March 2020|work=Deccan Herald|access-date=29 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The total number of confirmed cases reached 50.<ref name=\"29Bulletin\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcoronatn.in/files/Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_29_03_2020_1_Page_English_77_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=29 March 2020|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March, 17 new cases were reported, highest till date in the state<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" /> - 10 male patients from [[Erode]], all of whom have travelled to Delhi were in contact with the Thailand tourists, 5 in Chennai and 1 each in [[Karur]] and [[Madurai]].<ref name=\"30MarchBulletinOld\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_30_03_20_COVID_19_1_11_AM.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_30_03_20_COVID_19_1_11_AM.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March, 57 new cases were reported, all with a history of travel predominately to [[Delhi]], bringing the total to 124.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-reports-57-new-covid-19-cases-in-one-day-79-attended-tablighi-jamaat-state-tally-at-124-1661904-2020-03-31|title=Tamil Nadu reports 57 new Covid-19 cases in one day, 79% attended Tablighi Jamaat. State tally at 124|date=|work=India Today|access-date=1 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It was the highest single day rise till date. 50 of these cases were from [[Namakkal district|Namakkal]] (18), [[Tirunelveli district|Tirunelveli]] (22), Kanyakumari (4) [[Viluppuram|Villupuram]] (3), Madurai (2) and Thoothukudi (1), all had travel history to Delhi.<ref name=\"31MarBulletin2\" /> Officials had discovered that at least 80 out of 124 confirmed cases (79 per cent) in Tamil Nadu were from one cluster as they are direct or indirect contact of the two Thai nationals who had tested positive for on 21 March.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /><ref name=\"Hindu-31March\" />  The Thai nationals, identified as patients 5 and 6 were part of a large group from countries including Thailand, Indonesia, Malaysia, etc. who had visited the state for an annual pilgrimage.<ref name=\"Hindu-31March\">{{Cite news|last=M|first=Serena Josephine|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/25-of-67-patients-directly-or-indirectly-linked-to-thai-nationals/article31212197.ece|title=25 of 67 patients directly or indirectly linked to Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-31|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> This group had also attended a 3-day religious congregation event known as ''Tablighi Jamaat'' in [[New Delhi]]  in early March.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-25-out-of-67-in-tamil-nadu-have-contact-or-travel-history-with-thai-nationals-819372.html|title=Coronavirus: 25 out of 67 in Tamil Nadu have contact or travel history with Thai nationals|date=2020-03-30|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> It was estimated that more than 1,500 people from the state had participated in this event.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/coimbatore-erode-stare-at-crisis-as-tamil-nadu-govt-races-to-trace-scores-back-from-nizamuddin-event-2558131.html|title=Coimbatore, Erode Stare at Crisis as Tamil Nadu Govt Races to Trace Scores Back from Nizamuddin Event|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Officials also confirmed that the 54-year-old patient who had died the previous week had also participated in the gathering.  Of 1,500 people who were in the gathering, 1,130 had returned to the state. The government had identified and isolated 515 of the 1,130 people and faced difficulty while trying to map the rest.<ref name=\"IT-57cases\" /> It had urged people who attended the gathering to step forward and get tested.<ref name=\"31MarchNews18\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/tamil-nadu-reports-50-more-covid-19-cases/articleshow/74917772.cms|title=Tamil Nadu Coronavirus update: Tamil Nadu reports 50 more Covid-19 cases {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|last=Mar 31|first=Pushpa Narayan {{!}} TNN {{!}} Updated:|last2=2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01|last3=Ist|first3=23:31}}</ref>\n\n== Testing and treatment ==\nAs of 31 March, the state had 16 laboratories (10 government and 6 private) to handle testing for the coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/List_of_Private_Laboratories_to_test_COVID_19_30_03_2020_3_Pages_English_604_KB.pdf|title=List_of_Private_Laboratories_to_test_COVID_19_30_03_2020_3_Pages_English_604_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Goverment_COVID_19_Testing_Lab_ICMR_Support_29032020_5_Pages_English_589_KB.pdf|title=Goverment_COVID_19_Testing_Lab_ICMR_Support_29032020_5_Pages_English_589_KB.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref> Initially, it had four government labs.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://scroll.in/pulse/956278/why-kerala-has-done-more-coronavirus-tests-than-tamil-nadu-and-why-this-must-change|title=Why Kerala has done more coronavirus tests than Tamil Nadu \u2013 and why this must change|last=Yamunan|first=Sruthisagar|website=Scroll.in|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> During the first half of March, the state faced criticism for low number of tests. By 16 March, it had only tested 90 samples while neighboring Kerala and Karnataka had tested more than 1500 and 750 samples.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/in-tamil-nadu-patients-doctors-call-for-increased-tests-on-coronavirus/articleshow/74647117.cms|title=Coronavirus Tamil Nadu Updates: In Tamil Nadu, patients &amp; doctors call for increased tests on coronavirus {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|date=16 March 2020|agency=TNN |website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The director of Public Health defended the state\u2019s low number of tests saying that Kerala saw more travel from coronavirus-affected countries which is why it had detected more cases.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Public Health department has also said that the state follows test protocols established by the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare|Union Health Ministry]].<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn order to test community transmission, as of 16 March, the state had tested 22 random samples of people with influenza and severe acute respiratory infection for coronavirus as per ICMR guidelines. All tested negative.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBy 31 March, as part of the active surveillance, the government had surveyed 3,96,147 people in 1,08,677 houses in the containment and buffer zones of 12 affected districts for fever and other symptoms. It was carried out by over 2,000 personnel.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/tamil-nadu-coronavirus-cases-rises-to-74-nizamuddin-link-to-a-chunk-of-it-surfaces-819633.html|title=Tamil Nadu coronavirus cases rises to 74, Nizamuddin link to a chunk of it surfaces|date=2020-03-31|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nAs of 1 April 2079 samples have been tested of which, 124 were positive.<ref name=\"TNHFW\" />\n\n=== Containment measures ===\nThe [[Department of Health and Family Welfare (Tamil Nadu)|Department of Health and Family Welfare]] is responsible for testing and contact tracing the new cases in the state. On 24 March, stickers announcing that \"COVID-19/Do not Visit/Home under quarantine,\" with details such as name and number of people under watch were pasted on the doors of houses of foreign returnees. Authorities had also marked their arms with home quarantine stamps.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil-nadu/2020/mar/24/tamil-nadu-goes-under-lockdown-home-quarantine-stickers-pasted-on-doors-of-foreign-returnees-2121106.html|title=Tamil Nadu goes under lockdown; home quarantine stickers pasted on doors of foreign returnees|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> Government launched a mobile application to allow people under home quarantine to interact healthcare professionals for getting medical advice and counselling.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tamil-nadu-launches-app-to-provide-advice-to-those-under-home-quarantine-816562.html|title=Coronavirus: Tamil Nadu launches app to provide advice to those under home quarantine|date=2020-03-22|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, government announced plans for creating containment zones to stop the community spread.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/tamil-nadu-prepares-for-stage-two-of-coronavirus-outbreak-with-more-home-quarantines-surveillance-2555261.html|title=Tamil Nadu Prepares for Stage Two of Coronavirus Outbreak With More Home Quarantines, Surveillance|website=News18|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> On 31 March, the government said that it had started the monitoring process inside containment zones (5 sq.km radius of infected patients) set up across 12 districts. The containment zone is ringed by an additional 2 sq.km buffer zone.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAs of 31 March, '''74,533''' passengers who had returned from affected countries are being monitored under 28 day home quarantine. 3470 have completed this quarantine. '''79''' are currently in institutional quarantine facilities across the state.<ref name=\"Daily30Mar\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|title=Daily_Report_30_03_2020_COVID_19.pdf|last=|first=|date=|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Governmental response ==\nThe [[Government of Tamil Nadu|state government]] was among the first to launch measures against COVID-19.<ref name=\"TNborder\" /> On 30 January, it had put 78 people who arrived from China under quarantine.<ref name=\"TNborder\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/coronavirus-outbreak-tamil-nadu-closes-borders-constitutes-task-force-120032201274_1.html|title=Coronavirus outbreak: Tamil Nadu closes borders, constitutes task force|work=Business Standard India|access-date=21 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> It had allocated sum of {{INRConvert|60|c}} from disaster relief fund to deal with the crisis. On 15 March, the state government ordered closure of primary schools throughout the state while shutting theatres and malls in border districts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/tamil-nadu-govt-to-release-rs-60-crore-disaster-relief-funds-to-tackle-coronavirus-shuts-primary-schools-1655752-2020-03-15|title=Tamil Nadu govt to release Rs 60 crore disaster relief fund to tackle coronavirus, shuts primary schools|last=Lobo|first=Shalini|date=|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 March, the state government partially closed its borders with [[Karnataka]], [[Kerala]] and [[Andhra Pradesh]] on March 20 until March 31 and constituted a task force to closely monitor the preventive measures against the viral outbreak.<ref name=\"TNborder\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/tn-closes-border-roads-movement-of-essentials-allowed/1774787|title=TN closes border roads, movement of essentials allowed|last=|first=|date=|website=Outlook India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=21 March 2020}}</ref> On 21 March, the government postponed the Class 10 SSLC board exams to beyond April 14, which were due to begin from March 27.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu/covid-19-tamil-nadus-class-10-board-exams-postponed/article31127217.ece|title=COVID-19: Tamil Nadu's Class 10 board exams postponed|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, the government extended '[[Janata Curfew|''Janata curfew'']]' to Monday morning 5 am.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/tamil-nadu-govt-extends-janata-curfew-till-monday-morning/articleshow/74758800.cms|title=Tamil Nadu govt extends 'Janata curfew' till Monday morning|date=2020-03-22|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The next day, government announced that prohibitory orders under [[Unlawful assembly|section 144]] will start from 24 March 6 pm until March 31 which prohibits gatherings of more than 5 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/tn-imposes-section-144-week-no-gatherings-more-5-people-120912|title=TN imposes Section 144 for a week, no gatherings of more than 5 people|last=|first=|date=23 March 2020|website=www.thenewsminute.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=23 March 2020}}</ref> On the same day, [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Narendra Modi]] announced a[[2020 coronavirus lockdown in India|nationwide lockdown]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/23/asia/coronavirus-covid-19-update-india-intl-hnk/index.html|title=India places millions under lockdown to fight coronavirus|author1=Helen Regan |author2=Esha Mitra |author3=Swati Gupta|date=|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 24 March, Health Minister C. Vijayabaskar announced a hospital dedicated for treating COVID-19 patients. The newly built Omandurar Government Multispeciality Hospital was being converted into a special facility with 350 beds to treat COVID-19 patients exclusively.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kannan|first=Ramya|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/tamil-nadu-announces-dedicated-hospital-for-covid-19-patients/article31146741.ece|title=Tamil Nadu announces dedicated hospital for COVID-19 patients|date=2020-03-24|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> On 25 March, chief minister [[Edappadi K. Palaniswami|Edappadi K Palaniswami]] announced that students of class 1\u20139 in the state will be promoted automatically considering the closure of schools.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/class-1-9-students-will-be-promoted-in-tamil-nadu-due-to-closure-of-schools-cm-11585134717305.html|title=Class 1-9 students will be promoted in Tamil Nadu due to closure of schools: CM|last=|first=|date=25 March 2020|website=Livemint|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=25 March 2020}}</ref> After the nationwide lockdown, Chennai suspended delivery of cooked food from services like [[Swiggy]] and [[Zomato]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Shrivastava|first=Aditi|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/chennai-bans-delivery-of-cooked-food/articleshow/74837380.cms?from=mdr|title=Chennai bans delivery of cooked food|date=2020-03-27|work=The Economic Times|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://entrackr.com/2020/03/swiggy-and-zomato-not-allowed-to-deliver-in-tamil-nadu/|title=Swiggy and Zomato not allowed to deliver in Tamil Nadu|last=Upadhyay|first=Harsh|date=26 March 2020|website=Entrackr|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref> The services were allowed by the government after imposing some regulations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/covid-19-tamil-nadu-allows-swiggy-zomato-other-apps-to-home-deliver-cooked-food/articleshow/74852688.cms|title=Covid-19: Tamil Nadu allows Swiggy, Zomato, other apps to home deliver cooked food {{!}} Chennai News - Times of India|first=Ram |last=Sundaram |date=27 March 2020|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nThe government has established helplines for public.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/whomtocontact.html|title=Health & Family Welfare Department Government of Tamil Nadu Stop Corona Contact Information|website=stopcorona.tn.gov.in|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> It also released an app for officials monitor people under home quarantine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/national/south/coronavirus-tn-tracks-movements-of-home-quarantine-people-through-a-mobile-app-817853.html|title=Coronavirus: TN tracks movements of home quarantine people through a mobile app|date=2020-03-26|website=Deccan Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\nThe data below are based on Health and Family Welfare Department of Tamil Nadu daily reports.\n=== Cases ===\n{{Columns\n|col1='''Patient Number''':\n{{legend|#00FF00|Recovered (no detectable virus)}}\n{{legend|#FFFCBB|Clinically recovered}}\n{{legend|#D3D3D3|Under treatment/ Clearance not yet reported}}\n{{legend|#fbb|Deceased}}\n|col2='''Type of Transmission''':\n*{{legend|#adffe6|'''T''' \u2013 Travel-related}}\n*{{legend|#ffff96|'''T/PTP''' \u2013 Travel related person-to-person spread, usually family and close contacts}}\n*{{legend|#f5deb3|'''PTP''' \u2013 Person-to-person local or community spread (or of unclear origin)}}\n|col2width=55em\n|}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders collapsible\" style=\"width: 100%;\"\n! style=\"text-align:center\"; colspan=\"10\"; rowspan=\"1\" | Case list of confirmed infected patients in Tamil Nadu (since 7 March 2020)\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" |Patient Number\n! scope=\"col\" |No. of Persons\n! scope=\"col\" |Date Announced<br/>(2020)\n! scope=\"col\" |Origin type\n! scope=\"col\" |Origin\n! scope=\"col\" |Location\n! scope=\"col\" |Sex-Age\n!Admitted facility\n!Notes\n!Ref(s)\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center;background: #FFFCBB;\" |1\n!1\n! scope=\"row\" style=\"text-align:center\" |7 March\n| style=\"text-align:center;background:#adffe6;\" |'''T'''\n|[[Oman]]\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[Chennai]]\n|M-45\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Government General Hospital, Chennai|Rajiv Gandhi Government General Hospital]]\n|\n| rowspan=\"2\" |<ref name=\"29Bulletin\" /><ref name=\"30MarBulletin5pages\">{{Cite web|url=https://stopcorona.tn.gov.in/files/Media_Bulletin_30_03_2020.pdf|title=Media_Bulletin_30_03_2020.pdf|last=|first=|date=30 March 2020|website=Health and Family Welfare Department, Government of Tamil Nadu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row