0511001020/http://www.stat.kz/digital/naselsenie/2012/2013/%25D0%25BC%25D0%25B0%25D1%2580%25D1%2582/01_2012_%25D0%25AD-14-05-%25D0%259C.xls \u0427\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0420\u0435\u0441\u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0438 \u041a\u0430\u0437\u0430\u0445\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d \u043f\u043e \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044f\u043c \u0441 \u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u0430 2013 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0434\u043e 1 \u0444\u0435\u0432\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044f 2013 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430] (russisch; Excel-Datei; 55&nbsp;kB).</ref>\n| population_total        = 882961\n| population_as_of        = 2015-10-01\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| iso_code                = KZ-KUS\n| registration_plate      = 10, P \n| website                 = {{URL|http://www.kostanay.gov.kz}}\n| footnotes               = \n}}{{Lead too short|date=July 2019}}\n'''Kostanay Region''' ({{lang-kk|\u049a\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u044b\u0441\u044b|translit=Qostana\u0131 oblysy}}; {{lang-ru|\u041a\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u041e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u044c|translit=Kustanayskaya Oblast}}) is a [[Regions of Kazakhstan|region]] of [[Kazakhstan]]. Its administrative center is the city of [[Kostanay]].  The population of the region is 900,300.  The population living in Kostanay is 207,000 <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://kostanay.info/ru/ofdoc/20062010.shtml |title=Official site of Kostanay city |access-date=2008-01-15 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721215948/http://kostanay.info/ru/ofdoc/20062010.shtml |archive-date=2011-07-21 |url-status=dead }}</ref> which is equivalent to 23% of the region.\n\n==Geography==\nKostanay Region is adjacent to the [[Russia]]n [[Federal subjects of Russia|federal subjects]] [[Orenburg Oblast]], [[Chelyabinsk Oblast]], [[Kurgan Oblast]], and is near the [[Ural Mountains]]. It also touches four other Kazakh regions: [[Aktobe Region]] to the southwest, [[Karaganda Region]] to the south, [[Akmola Region]] to the southeast, and [[North Kazakhstan Region]] to the northeast. The [[Tobol River|Tobol (Tobyl) River]], a tributary of the [[Irtysh|Irtysh River]], starts in and flows through the region on its way to Russia. Kostanay Region's area is 197,000 square kilometers, making it the sixth largest of the Kazakh regions.\n\n===Flora and fauna===\nResources of an animal and flora of Kostanay Region are suitable for the organization and development of zones and objects of civilized fishery and a hunt, lake-commodity fish culture, hunt facilities development. The fauna of ground animal includes 52 kinds of [[mammal]], 267 is constant or temporarily living [[bird]]s, 10 kinds of amphibious and kowtowing, in reservoirs 24 kinds of [[fish]]es live.\n\n''Naurzum reserve'' (877&nbsp;km\u00b2), 3 natural sanctuaries (1630&nbsp;km\u00b2) and 12 state nature sanctuaries (0.47&nbsp;km\u00b2) with a rich vegetative cover are pride of region.\n\n===Natural resources===\nThe territory of region is characterized by rather flat relief with inflows of the rivers: Ayat, Ubagan, Ui, Torgai with inflows of the rivers: Saryozen, Kara. The Northern part occupy southeast suburb of the West-Siberian lowland, to the south from it is situated Torgai plateau; in the west - wavy plain Zaural plateau and in a southwest Saryarka spurs. River network is rare. Within the limits of the region it is totaled about 310 fine rivers. The largest rivers - [[Tobol River|Tobol]] and Torgai. On the river Tobol are Verhnetobolsk, Karatomar and Amangeldy water basins. In Kostanay Region are more than 5 thousand lakes. Largest of them are located in Torgai dell - Kusmyryn, Sarymoin, Aksuat, Sarykopa. Woodland area 2,175&nbsp;km\u00b2 including 1,512&nbsp;km\u00b2 natural plantings. In connection with the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[Virgin Lands Campaign]], much of the area was ploughed for [[wheat]].  The Kostanay Region is rich in minerals, especially [[iron ore]] (deposits of magnetite ores - Sokolovsk, Sarbaiskoe, Kachary and brown soolits iron ores - Ayatsk iron ore pool, Lisakovsk deposit). The total stock of magnetite's ores and hematite's makes 15,7 billion tons, of them easy enrich and not demanding enrichment - 5,7 billion tons. Especially bowels are rich in iron ore, [[Lignite|brown coal]], asbestos, fire-resistant and brick clay, flux and cement limestone, glass sand, a building stone and others. Opened 19 deposits of [[bauxite]], 7 - [[gold]], on one of [[silver]] and [[nickel]]. In northern part of area chernozems and pine forests (Arakaragai, Amankaragai) prevail; in the central part - chestnut ground with pine forest Naurzimkaragai on the basis of which the same reserve is organized; the southern part is dominated by grasslands and shrublands.\n\n===Water===\nThe region center, Kostanay, is supplied with water from Amangeldinsky water basins (underground volume 6,7 million cubic meters) and Kostanay deposit of underground waters (operational stocks - 33.5 million cube. m). The city of Lisakovsk gets water from the Verhnetobols water basins (underground volume totals 814 million cubic meters). Regional centers Sarykol, Karasu, Uzunkol are supplied with water with Ishim water supply line and S\u0435rgeevsk water basin which is on the territory of the North-Kazakhstan region. 12 big water supply lines on the territory of Kostanay region give water to more than 220 settlements and 5 regional centers. Water delivery of other areas is carried out from local sources (deposits of underground waters). Karatomar water basins (underground volume 516 million cube. m) supply [[Rudni]], \u041a\u0430char region and Fedorovka.\n<ref>http://www.kostanay.net/modules/about/article.php?storyid=2 Information about Kostanay</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nKostanay Region's climate is continental, with strongly pronounced alternation of four seasons. Average temperatures: January: -18 to -19 \u00b0\u0421, July: 19 to 22 \u00b0\u0421. In the winter, the temperature can be as cold as -25 to -30 \u00b0C. In summer, the temperature can reach 30 \u00b0C. Annual amount of precipitation is 300\u2013350&nbsp;mm in the northern areas and 240 to 280&nbsp;mm in the south. The growing season is about 150 to 175 days in the north and 180 days in the south.\n\n==Demographics==\n{{refimprove|date=June 2012}}\n\n[[File:Kazakhstan European Rus.png|thumb|500px|{{legend-table|title=The share of the European population by districts and cities of regional and republican subordination Kazakhstan in 2016\n|#530132|> 70\u066a\n|#82004D|60.0 \u2013 69.9 %\n|#B4006B|50.0 - 59.9 %\n|#FF0097|40.0 - 49.9 %\n|#FF9AC7|30.0 - 39.9 %\n|#FCC7DF|20.0 - 29.9 %\n|#FBE7F0|10.0 - 19.9 %\n|#ffffff|0.0 - 9.9 %\n}}]]\n\nAccording to the 1999 census, the major ethnic groups are Russians (42.27%) and Kazakhs (30.93%). Most important minorities are Ukrainians (12.82%), Germans (5.64%), Belarusians (2.46%), Tatars (1.97%), Poles (0.21%) and Others (3.70%). The [[Madjars]] are a special ethnic group living in the Torgay area.\n\nAs of December 2006, Kazakhs accounted for 33.8% of the population and Russians accounted for 41.7%. The percentage of Germans had decreased to 3.9%.\n\nPopulation (2009): 886,300 people (5.7%, 6th)\n \nDensity: {{convert|4.5|km2|abbr=on}} (8th)\n \nNational structure: Kazakhs \u2014 46.6%; Russians \u2014 28.6%\n \nArea: {{convert|196000|km2|abbr=on}} (7.2%, 6th)\n\n==Administrative divisions==\nThe region is administratively divided into sixteen districts and the cities of [[Kostanay]], [[Arkalyk]], [[Lisakovsk]], and [[Rudny, Kazakhstan|Rudny]].<ref name=\"akimat-reg\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kostanay.gov.kz/eng/kostanaiskaja_oblast-12%7c36.html|title=Region\u2019s districts|publisher=Kostanay Region's Akimat|accessdate=10 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111027231059/http://www.kostanay.gov.kz/eng/kostanaiskaja_oblast-12%7C36.html|archive-date=2011-10-27|url-status=dead}}</ref> \n# [[Altynsarin District]], with the administrative center in the [[Village#Central and Eastern Europe|selo]] of [[Obagan]];\n# [[Amangeldi District]], the selo of [[Amangeldi]];\n# [[Auliekol District]], the selo of [[Auliekol]];\n# [[Denisov District]], the settlement of [[Denisovka, Kazakhstan|Denisovka]];\n# [[Fyodorov District]], the selo of [[Fyodorovka, Fyodorov District|Fyodorovka]];\n# [[Kamysty District]], the selo of [[Kamysty]];\n# [[Karabalyk District]], the urban-type settlement of [[Karabalyk]];\n# [[Karasu District]], the selo of [[Karasu, Kazakhstan|Karasu]];\n# [[Kostanay District]], the urban-type settlement of [[Zatobolsk]];\n# [[Mendykara District]], the selo of [[Borovskoye, Kazakhstan|Borovskoye]];\n# [[Nauyrzym District]], the selo of [[Karamendy]];\n# [[Sarykol District]], the urban-type settlement of [[Sarykol, Kostanay Region|Sarykol]];\n# [[Taran District]], the selo of [[Taran, Kazakhstan|Taran]];\n# [[Uzunkol District]], the selo of [[Uzunkol]];\n# [[Zhangeldi District]], the selo of [[Torgay]];\n# [[Zhetikara District|Zhitikara District]], the town of [[Zhetikara|Zhitikara]].\n\n* The following five localities in Kostanay Region have town status:<ref name=\"akimat-reg\"/> [[Kostanay]], [[Arkalyk]], [[Lisakovsk]], [[Rudny, Kazakhstan|Rudny]], and [[Zhetikara]].\n\n==Public institutions==\nKostanay Region function 8 higher educational institutions: 4 state and 4 not state, and also 6 branches of the Kazakhstan and Russian high schools. One of the basic - Kostanay State University (named after [[Akhmet Baytursinuli]]). The total number of students is made by 23,6 thousand person. Also functions 22 colleges in which it is trained over 12,2 thousand pupils.\n\nIn 2002-2003 educational year work 723 schools, with a contingent of pupils - 155,5 thousand person.\n\nThe state network of culture totals 380 libraries, 201 club establishments, 8 museums, 2 theatres: I. Omarov regional Kazakh drama theatre and regional Russian drama theatre. The regional showroom works.\n\nThere are sport objects: two palaces of sports, 26 stadiums, 10 sports complexes and 567 sports halls.\n\n==Communications==\nKostanay Region has steady automobile outputs in all next regions and the regional centers.  The Extent of general-purpose highways makes 9133&nbsp;km, republican value - 1401&nbsp;km and local - 7732&nbsp;km. On territory of area pass from the north on the south and a southeast the main transit roads connecting the regional center with cities of Kazakhstan: [[Nur-Sultan]], [[Almaty]] and adjoining areas; Urals: [[Chelyabinsk]], [[Magnitogorsk]], [[Troitsk]], [[Ekaterinburg]]; Western Siberia: [[Kurgan, Kurgan Oblast|Kurgan]], [[Tyumen]].\n\nOperation length of railways of general purpose, which are taking place on territory of the region, is equal to 1048&nbsp;km.  Function 53 stations conducting cargo and passenger transportations which cover all cities and 11 region.\n\nIn Kostanay Region are available three airports with a firm covering of runways: in cities of Kostanay and Arkalyk, settlement Torgai. Runways of the airport of Kostanay can accept types of planes: Tu-134, Tu-154, \u0410\u041d-22, Il-86 and the [[Boeing]]. From the international [[Kostanay Airport|airport of Kostanay]] regular and charter flights in many cities of Kazakhstan, the [[Commonwealth of Independent States|CIS]], [[Germany]] ([[Frankfurt on Main]], [[D\u00fcsseldorf]], [[Hamburg]], [[Stuttgart]]), to [[Arab Emirates]], [[Turkey]] and others are carried out. Here there are points of the boundary and customs control. Mineral oil in Kostanay Region is delivered from the [[Russia|Russian Federation]] and from oil refineries of Kazakhstan by railway.\n\nThe basic monopolist in sphere of telecommunications in Kostanay Region is the branch of \"Kazaktelekom\". The big development was received with a global network the Internet, cellular communication, an IP-telephony.\n\n==Health==\nIn sanatorium ''Sosnoviy bor'' there are [[Hydrotherapy|hydropathic establishments]], which are located on medical sources and have interrepublican value. Treatment is carried out: a [[gastrointestinal tract]], [[respiratory system]], postoperative rehabilitation and a [[mud bath]]s.\n\n==Notable People==\n* [[Kamshat Donenbaeva]] (1943-2017), 3-term delegate to the Supreme Soviet of the USSR<ref>{{cite news |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=\u0421\u043a\u043e\u043d\u0447\u0430\u043b\u0430\u0441\u044c \u041a\u0430\u043c\u0448\u0430\u0442 \u0414\u043e\u043d\u0435\u043d\u0431\u0430\u0435\u0432\u0430 |url=http://www.ng.kz/modules/news/article.php?storyid=28671 |accessdate=8 November 2018 |newspaper=\u041d\u0430\u0448\u0430 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 |date=10 November 2017 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20181108190248/http://www.ng.kz/modules/news/article.php?storyid=28671 |archivedate=8 November 2018 |location=Kostanay, Kazakhstan |trans-title=Kamshat Donenbayeva dies}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* http://www.kostanay.gov.kz\n\n===References===\n{{commonscat|Qostanay Province}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Geographic location\n|Centre    = Kostanay Region\n|North     = {{flag|Chelyabinsk Oblast}} and {{flag|Kurgan Oblast}},  {{flag|Russia}}\n|Northeast = [[North Kazakhstan Region]]\n|East      = [[Akmola Region]]\n|Southeast = [[Karaganda Region]]\n|South     = \n|Southwest = [[Aktobe Region]]\n|West      = {{flag|Orenburg Oblast}},  {{flag|Russia}}\n|Northwest = \n}}\n\n{{Kostanay Region}}\n{{Regions of Kazakhstan}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Kostanay Region| ]]\n[[Category:Regions of Kazakhstan]]\n", "name_user": "N.baltabayeva", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(added the section \"Tourism\", with a description of attractions, recreation areas, and archaeological complexes)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kostanay_Region"}
{"title_page": "PM CARES Fund", "text_new": "The '''Prime Minister's Citizen Assistance and Relief in Emergency Situations Fund''' '''(PM CARES Fund)''' was created on 28 March 2020 following the [[COVID-19 pandemic in India]]. The fund will be used for combating, containment and relief efforts against the coronavirus outbreak and similar pandemic like situations in the future. The Prime Minister is the chairman of the trust. Members will include the defence, home and finance ministers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/pm-cares-pm-narendra-modi-announces-new-covid-19-fund-gets-rs-25-crore-from-akshay-kumar-2202275|title=PM Modi Announces New COVID-19 Fund, Gets Rs 25 Crore From Akshay Kumar|last=|first=|date=|editor-last=Roy|editor-first=Divyanshu Dutta|website=NDTV|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsonair.com/Main-News-Details.aspx?id=384047|title=People urged to donate generously in PM CARES fund; PM Modi says every contribution matters|website=newsonair.com|access-date=2020-03-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/pm-narendra-modi-announces-pm-cares-fund-to-fight-coronavirus-outbreak-120032900031_1.html|title=PM Narendra Modi announces PM-CARES fund to fight coronavirus outbreak|date=2020-03-29|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2020-03-29|url-status=live|others=PTI}}</ref>\n\nThe fund will also enable [[micro-donation]]s.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Sharma|first=Sandhya|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/tech/internet/cyber-chiefs-warning-as-hackers-target-pms-covid-fund/articleshow/74877953.cms|title=Cyber chief's warning as hackers target PM's Covid fund|date=2020-03-29|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref> The minimum donation accepted for the PM CARES Fund is {{INRConvert|10||lk=on|year=2020}}.<ref name=\":3\" /> The donations will be tax exempt and fall under [[corporate social responsibility]].<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/policy/donation-to-pm-cares-fund-to-be-fully-exempted-under-income-tax-act/article31221733.ece|title=Donation to PM CARES Fund to be fully exempted section 80G of I-T Act|last=|first=|date=31 March 2020|website=The Hindu @businessline|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> The Prime Minister had said that the [[Prime Minister's Office (India)|PMO]] had received many requests to help in the war against COVID-19. Accordingly, the fund was set up and will be used for disaster management and research.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dqindia.com/pm-cares-fund-need-know/|title=PM CARES Fund: All You Need to Know|date=2020-03-30|website=DATAQUEST|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/pm-modi-announces-emergency-relief-fund-for-coronavirus-fight/articleshow/74863297.cms|title=PM Modi announces emergency relief fund for coronavirus fight|date=2020-03-28|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 March, Syed Ataur Rahman, a citizen of India, donated {{INRConvert|501||lk=on|year=2020}} to the fund tweeting about it as \"just a little donation\". PM Modi tweeted back that \"There\u2019s nothing big or little. Every single contribution matters. It shows our collective resolve to defeat COVID-19.\"<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/prime-minister-narendra-modi-to-man-who-donated-rs-501-to-covid-19-coronavirus-fund-nothing-big-or-l-2202366|title=\"Nothing Big Or Little\": PM To Man Who Donated Rs 501 To COVID-19 Fund|last=|first=|date=|website=NDTV|others=PTI|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n\n== About ==\nAny contribution made to the PM CARES Fund before 30 June would qualify for a full amount of [[tax exemption]] under (80G) [[The Income-tax Act, 1961|Income Tax Act, 1961]].<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Noronha|first=Gaurav|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/economy/policy/govt-clarifies-on-companys-contributions-to-pm-cares-fund-above-csr-limit/articleshow/74907220.cms|title=Govt clarifies on company's contributions to PM CARES Fund above CSR limit|date=2020-03-31|work=The Economic Times|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" /> The [[Ministry of Corporate Affairs]] announced that contributions to the PM CARES fund would be counted as part of the companies corporate social responsibility with additional CSR being offset in subsequent years.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe PM CARES fund is different from the [[Prime Minister's National Relief Fund]] (PMNRF), which was created in 1948 and has been used by the [[Government of India]] ever since, for example during the recent [[2013 North India floods]], the [[2015 South India floods]] and the [[2019 Kerala floods]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.pmindia.gov.in/en/pms-funds/|title=PM National Relief Fund {{!}} Prime Minister of India|website=www.pmindia.gov.in|language=en|access-date=2018-06-06}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the creation of the fund opposition members raised a queries as to why a separate fund was needed, when it was registered, under which act and why it did not contain any members of civil society or opposition as part of the trust.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/congress-questions-setting-up-of-pm-cares-fund-to-deal-with-coronavirus/article31210904.ece|title=Congress questions setting up of PM CARES Fund to deal with coronavirus|date=2020-03-30|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-31|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> [[Business Today (India)|Business Today]] reported that government sources justified creation of the fund saying that PMNRF is for natural disasters, while PM CARES Fund is for COVID-19 similar pandemic situations.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/pm-cares-fund-better-suited-tto-deal-with-coronavirus-crisis-say-legal-experts/story/399670.html|title=PM CARES Fund better suited to deal with coronavirus crisis, say legal experts|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> It was also mentioned that the [[Consolidated Fund of India]] needs legislative jurisdiction to be used; creation of a fund like the PM CARES Fund takes care of legislative hurdles.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nImmediately after the fund was created a number of fake accounts popped up. While the original [[Unified Payments Interface|UPI]] account was PMCARES@SBI, [[Delhi Police]] booked unknown individuals for creating an account removing the 'S', PMCARE@SBI, intended to scam people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/delhi-police-books-fraudsters-for-making-fake-sbi-account-of-pm-s-covid-19-relief-fund-1661272-2020-03-30|title=Delhi Police books fraudsters for making fake SBI account of PM's Covid-19 Relief Fund|last=Ojha|first=Arvind|date=30 March 2020|website=India Today|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n\n== Contributions ==\nThe day the fund was announced, Syed Ataur Rahman, a citizen of India, donated {{INRConvert|501||lk=on|year=2020}} tweeting about it as \"just a little donation\". PM Modi tweeted back that \"There\u2019s nothing big or little. Every single contribution matters. It shows our collective resolve to defeat COVID-19.\"<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nFollowing is an incomplete list of contributions to the PM CARES Fund above {{INRConvert|25|c|lk=on|year=2020}} for companies and above {{INRConvert|10|c|lk=on|year=2020}} for individuals:\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Incomplete list of contributions\n!Name of company/PSU\n!Amount (Rs)\n!Name of person\n!Amount (Rs)\n|-\n|[[Tata Group]] (Tata Sons and Tata Trusts)\n|{{INRConvert|1500|c|lk=on|year=2020}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B-ZtNZKBroO/?igshid=mldr8ae8sev4|title=Tata Group commits INR 500 crores for PM-CARES out of total INR 1500 crores to fight Covid-19|last=Khera|first=Karan|date=2020-03-31|website=Company Statement|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Reliance Industries Limited]]\n|{{INRConvert|5000|c|lk=on|year=2020}}<ref>{{Cite news|last=Pathak|first=Kalpana|url=https://www.livemint.com/companies/news/covid-19-reliance-industries-commits-rs-500-cr-to-pm-cares-fund-11585577416645.html|title=Covid-19: Reliance Industries commits \u20b9500 cr to PM-CARES Fund|date=30 March 2020|work=Live Mint|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|[[Akshay Kumar]]\n|{{INRConvert|25|c|lk=on|year=2020}}<ref>{{Cite news|last=Kukreja|first=Monika|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/bollywood/pm-narendra-modi-applauds-akshay-kumar-for-rs-25-cr-donation-calls-it-a-great-gesture/story-6XRAkARvMlXBLrTNnkiAZN.html|title=PM Narendra Modi applauds Akshay Kumar for Rs 25 cr donation, calls it a \u2018great gesture\u2019|date=30 March 2020|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Oil and Natural Gas Corporation]]\n|{{INRConvert|300|c|lk=on|year=2020}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ongcindia.com/wps/wcm/connect/en/media/press-release/ongc-contributes-300crore-pmcares-fund|title=ONGC contributes Rs 300 crore to PM Cares Fund to combat COVID-19|date=30 March 2020|website=www.ongcindia.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n|[[Bhushan Kumar]]\n|{{INRConvert|11|c|lk=on|year=2020}}<ref name=\":6\" />\n|-\n|[[Indian Railways]]\n|{{INRConvert|151|c|lk=on|year=2020}}<ref name=\":6\" />\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Larsen & Toubro]]\n|{{INRConvert|150|c|lk=on|year=2020}}<ref>{{Cite news|last=Prasad|first=Rachita|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/indl-goods/svs/engineering/lt-donates-rs-150-crore-to-pm-cares-commits-to-pay-160000-contract-labourers-despite-disruption-in-work/articleshow/74884470.cms?from=mdr|title=L&T donates Rs 150 crore to PM-Cares, commits to pay 160,000 contract labourers despite disruption in work|date=30 March 2020|work=The Economic Times|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Central Armed Police Forces]]\n|{{INRConvert|116|c|lk=on|year=2020}}<ref name=\":6\" />\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Adani Foundation]]\n|{{INRConvert|100|c|lk=on|year=2020}}<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.business-standard.com/multimedia/video-gallery/general/covid-19-patanjali-to-contribute-rs-25-crore-to-pm-cares-fund-101941.htm|title=Donations Pour In For PM Cares Fund For Coronavirus: From Akshay Kumar To Champion Shooter Esha Singh|last=day|first=Jinal Bhatt 1|date=2020-03-30|website=Mashable India|language=en-in|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Bajaj Group]]\n|{{INRConvert|100|c|lk=on|year=2020}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fortuneindia.com/macro/tata-group-commits-1500-crore-to-fight-covid-19/104341|title=Tata group commits \u20b91,500 crore to fight Covid-19|website=www.fortuneindia.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[JSW Group]]\n|{{INRConvert|100|c|lk=on|year=2020}}<ref>{{Cite news|last=Dilipkumar|first=Bhavya|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/company/corporate-trends/jsw-announces-rs-100-crores-contribution-to-pm-cares-converts-some-facilities-into-isolation-wards/articleshow/74872384.cms|title=JSW announces Rs 100 crores contribution to PM-CARES, converts some facilities into isolation wards|date=29 March 2020|work=The Economic Ttimes|access-date=31 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|\n|\n|-\n|[[Torrent Group]]\n|{{INRConvert|100|c|lk=on|year=2020}}<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jayakumar|first=PB|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/corporate/torrent-group-commits-rs-100-crore-to-fight-coronavirus-pandemic/story/399668.html|title=Torrent Group commits Rs 100 crore to fight coronavirus pandemic|date=31 March 2020|work=Business Today|