{"title_page": "Masta Killa", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Masta Killa\n| image               = Masta Killa in Paris 2013.jpg\n| caption             = Masta Killa performing in Paris.\n| image_size          = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| landscape = yes\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Elgin Turner\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1970|8|18}}<ref name=Allmusic_bio>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/masta-killa-mn0000378021/biography |title=Masta Killa Biography |website=AllMusic |date= |author=Cyril Cordor |accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref>\n| birth_place         = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U.S.\n| alias           = Jamel Irief, Noodles, High Chief\n| genre               = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| occupation          = [[rapping|Rapper]]\n| years_active        = 1991\u2013present\n| label               = [[Nature Sounds]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Wu-Tang Clan]] \n| website             = [https://mastakillamusic.net https://mastakillamusic.net]\n}}\n'''Jamel Irief''' (born '''Elgin Turner'''; August 18, 1970), better known by his stage name '''Masta Killa''', is an American [[rapping|rapper]] and member of the [[Wu-Tang Clan]].<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207131840/http://music.msn.com/music/artist/masta-killa/ |url=http://music.msn.com/music/artist/masta-killa/ |title=Masta Killa on MSN Music |website=MSN Music |archivedate=December 7, 2013 |date= |accessdate=August 19, 2010}}</ref> Though one of the lesser-known members of the group (he was featured on only one track on their 1993 debut album ''[[Enter the Wu-Tang (36 Chambers)]]''), he has been prolific on Clan group albums and solo projects since the mid-1990s. He released his debut album ''[[No Said Date]]'' in 2004 to positive reviews, and has since released three additional albums.\n\n== Biography ==\n{{cquote| I never performed until we launched Wu-Tang. That was my first time as an MC. I have history since [[elementary school]] doing talent shows. [[breakdancing|Breaking]] and shit like that. I was that kind of dude. I loved to [[poplocking|pop]]. That was me. Always doing shit around music. As far as with a mic in my hand, Wu-Tang was the first time. There never was next level for me. It was Wu-Tang and that was it. I never tried to get on. Never looked for any of this, because it was never my vision. I'm kinda like hanging out with [[GZA]], and just stumbled across some shit. \"Oh word?\" And I was like, \"Maybe I can do this.\" When I was young going to clubs, I was just hanging out. I never went in there like I was trying to be an MC. I never tried to get a record deal, or pass out tapes. It's just been Wu-Tang and I'm here.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mvremix.com/urban/interviews/masta_killa_06.shtml |title=MVRemix Urban Interviews \u2013 Masta Killa |author=Noah Fowle |date=August 2006 |website=MVRemix.com |accessdate=August 19, 2010}}</ref>}}\n[[File:Wu-Tang Clan at Budapest Park - 2015.07.07 (13).JPG|thumb|Masta Killa at Budapest Park]]\nBorn in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City|New York]], Masta Killa was the last member to join the Wu-Tang Clan; consequently he did not appear on the group's debut single \"Protect Ya Neck\". He was also the only member who was not a rapper at the time of the group's formation. He was extensively mentored by the [[GZA]] during his early days with the group, evident in the similar flow they both employ. He derived his rap name from the 1978 [[kung fu]] film ''[[The 36th Chamber of Shaolin|Shaolin Master Killer]]'', (Shao Lin san shi liu fang). Masta only appeared on one track on the Wu-Tang Clan's first album, in the closing verse to \"Da Mystery of Chessboxin\". Masta only narrowly made the track, and was almost left off in favor of [[Killah Priest]]. In fact, on the ''No Said Date'' DVD, Killah Priest claims that he and Masta Killa were in competition for the spot on \"Da Mystery of Chessboxin'\", and while Killah Priest fell asleep, Masta Killa stayed up all night writing and Killah Priest woke up the next morning to Masta Killa's verse. Since he was a developing rapper at the time ''[[Enter the Wu-Tang (36 Chambers)]]'' was being written, his verse in \"Da Mystery of Chessboxin\" was the only one that could hold up with the other, more experienced Wu-Tang members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rapreviews.com/interview/mkilla06.html |title=RapReview Feature for October 3, 2006 \u2013 Masta Killa Interview |website=RapReviews.com |author=Adam Bernard  |date=October 3, 2006 |accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring the first round of solo projects, he made several appearances on tracks now considered Wu-Tang classics, such as \"Winter Warz\", \"Duel of the Iron Mic\", and \"Glaciers of Ice\". His flow at the time attracted attention for being very slow and laid-back, in contrast to the more manic, forceful styles of members like [[Inspectah Deck]] and [[Ghostface Killah]]. Masta Killa is also the Clansman fondest of [[China|Chinese]] [[martial art]]s imagery. In 1997, the Wu-Tang Clan's second album ''[[Wu-Tang Forever]]'' saw Masta become a mainstay in the group's line-up with regular appearances throughout the double album.\n\nMasta Killa was the last member to release a solo project, after it was delayed for several years and finally released in June 2004 with the title ''[[No Said Date]]''; critically acclaimed, it became independent label [[Nature Sounds]]' best-selling album, notable for featuring every core member of the Wu-Tang Clan on the album after a period in the group's history that lacked unity. His second album, ''[[Made in Brooklyn]]'', was released on August 8, 2006, and includes production from [[Pete Rock]] and [[MF Doom]]. \"Ringing Bells\", the [[Wu-Tang Clan affiliates#Bronze Nazareth|Bronze Nazareth]]-produced lead single from the album, was released in March 2006. Also in 2006, Masta Killa became the latest in a succession of hip hop artists to endorse [[PETA]], and participated in an advertisement for the organization to promote [[animal rights]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.contactmusic.net/wu-tang-clan/news/masta-killa-praised-for-being-animal-friendly_1057451 |title=Masta Killa Praised For Being Animal-friendly |website=contactmusic.net |date=January 25, 2008 |accessdate=March 6, 2017 |quote=I'll do anything that's going to save animals. Anytime I can encourage people to think twice before doing anything to animals that's a good thing.}}</ref> and a [[vegetarian]] lifestyle.<ref name=PETA>{{cite web |url=http://www.peta.org/videos/masta-killa-vegetarian-testimonial/ |title=Masta Killa: Vegetarian Testimonial |website=PETA.org |date= |author= |accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012 he released his third album titled ''[[Selling My Soul]]'', an LP with heavy soul grooves and guests including [[Kurupt]] and the late [[Ol' Dirty Bastard]]. The album was intended as a precursor to his long-awaited album ''Loyalty is Royalty'', first announced in 2010 and eventually released in 2017.<ref name=SMS_announce>{{cite web |url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.21606/title.masta-killa-announces-new-album-selling-my-soul-due-december-11th |title=Masta Killa Announces New Album \"Selling My Soul,\" Due December 11th |website=HipHopDX |date=October 22, 2012 |author=Steven Horowitz |accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref><ref name=LIR_2010>{{cite web |url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.10865/title.masta-killa-preps-live-loyalty-is-royalty-soul-substance |title=Masta Killa Preps \"Live,\" \"Loyalty Is Royalty\" & \"Soul & Substance\" |website=HipHopDX |date=March 21, 2010 |author=Paul Arnold |accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn the Wu-Tang Corp. website, Masta Killa stated, \"I know I seem serious and quiet to a lot of the fans. That's because I take my work seriously. It's not a game. The Clan and I work hard to give you the best.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wutang-corp.com/artists/wu-artist.php?id=5 |title=Masta Killa Biography at Wu-Tang Corp. \u2013 The Official Site of the Wu-Tang Clan |website=Wu-Tang Corp. |date= |accessdate=April 24, 2014}}</ref> He is a fan of [[Gladys Knight]], [[Patti LaBelle]], [[Barry White]], [[Parliament-Funkadelic]] and [[Ohio Players]].<ref name=NobSm_Int_Pt2>{{cite web|url=http://www.nobodysmiling.com/hiphop/interview/86569.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060823040612/http://www.nobodysmiling.com/hiphop/interview/86569.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 23, 2006 |title=Masta Killa \u2013 Lion Heart Pt.2 \u2013 Interview |website=Nobody Smiling |date= |author=Michael Ivey |accessdate=June 24, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\nLike fellow Wu-Tang Clan members [[GZA]] and [[RZA]], Masta Killa is a [[vegetarian]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Reskin |first=Lauren |url=http://blogs.miaminewtimes.com/shortorder/2010/06/meatless_in_miami_vegetarians.php |title=Meatless in Miami: Vegetarians in Popular Song |website=Miami New Times |date=June 16, 2010 |accessdate=August 19, 2010}}</ref>\n\nMasta Killa is related to both [[Marvin Gaye]] and [[Nat Turner]], as revealed in the 2019 Wu-Tang documentary \u2018\u2019[[Of Mics and Men]]\u2019\u2019.\n\n==Moniker and aliases==\nMasta Killa gets his name from the 1978 kung fu movie ''[[Shaolin Master Killer]]'', also known as the ''[[36th Chamber of Shaolin]]''. He is often referred to as Jamel Irief.<ref name=NobSm_Int_Pt1>{{cite web|url=http://www.nobodysmiling.com/hiphop/interview/86565.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060813122804/http://www.nobodysmiling.com/hiphop/interview/86565.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 13, 2006 |title=Masta Killa \u2013 Lion Heart Pt.1 \u2013 Interview |website=Nobody Smiling |date= |author=Michael Ivey |accessdate=June 24, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Masta Killa discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n* ''[[No Said Date]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Made in Brooklyn]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Selling My Soul]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Loyalty is Royalty]]'' (2017)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.myspace.com/mastakilla Masta Killa's Myspace]\n* [http://wutang-corp.com/artists/wu-artist.php?id=5 Masta Killa Biography]\n\n{{Masta Killa}}\n{{Wu-Tang Clan}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Masta Killa}}\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:Five percenters]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Wu-Tang Clan members]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Masta Killa\n| image               = Masta Killa in Paris 2013.jpg\n| caption             = Masta Killa performing in Paris.\n| image_size          = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| landscape = yes\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Elgin Turner\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1969|8|18}}<ref name=Allmusic_bio>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/masta-killa-mn0000378021/biography |title=Masta Killa Biography |website=AllMusic |date= |author=Cyril Cordor |accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref>\n| origin              = [[East New York]], [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City]]\n| alias           = Jamel Irief, Noodles, High Chief\n| genre               = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| occupation          = [[rapping|Rapper]]\n| years_active        = 1992\u2013present\n| label               = [[Nature Sounds]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Wu-Tang Clan]] \n| website             = [https://mastakillamusic.net https://mastakillamusic.net]\n}}\n'''Jamel Irief''' (born '''Elgin Turner'''; August 18, 1969), better known by his stage name '''Masta Killa''', is an American [[rapping|rapper]] and member of the [[Wu-Tang Clan]].<ref>{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207131840/http://music.msn.com/music/artist/masta-killa/ |url=http://music.msn.com/music/artist/masta-killa/ |title=Masta Killa on MSN Music |website=MSN Music |archivedate=December 7, 2013 |date= |accessdate=August 19, 2010}}</ref> Though one of the lesser-known members of the group (he was featured on only one track on their 1993 debut album ''[[Enter the Wu-Tang (36 Chambers)]]''), he has been prolific on Clan group albums and solo projects since the mid-1990s. He released his debut album ''[[No Said Date]]'' in 2004 to positive reviews, and has since released three additional albums.\n\n== Biography ==\n{{cquote| I never performed until we launched Wu-Tang. That was my first time as an MC. I have history since [[elementary school]] doing talent shows. [[breakdancing|Breaking]] and shit like that. I was that kind of dude. I loved to [[poplocking|pop]]. That was me. Always doing shit around music. As far as with a mic in my hand, Wu-Tang was the first time. There never was next level for me. It was Wu-Tang and that was it. I never tried to get on. Never looked for any of this, because it was never my vision. I'm kinda like hanging out with [[GZA]], and just stumbled across some shit. \"Oh word?\" And I was like, \"Maybe I can do this.\" When I was young going to clubs, I was just hanging out. I never went in there like I was trying to be an MC. I never tried to get a record deal, or pass out tapes. It's just been Wu-Tang and I'm here.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mvremix.com/urban/interviews/masta_killa_06.shtml |title=MVRemix Urban Interviews \u2013 Masta Killa |author=Noah Fowle |date=August 2006 |website=MVRemix.com |accessdate=August 19, 2010}}</ref>}}\n[[File:Wu-Tang Clan at Budapest Park - 2015.07.07 (13).JPG|thumb|Masta Killa at Budapest Park]]\nBorn in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York City|New York]], Masta Killa was the last member to join the Wu-Tang Clan; consequently he did not appear on the group's debut single \"Protect Ya Neck\". He was also the only member who was not a rapper at the time of the group's formation. He was extensively mentored by the [[GZA]] during his early days with the group, evident in the similar flow they both employ. He derived his rap name from the 1978 [[kung fu]] film ''[[The 36th Chamber of Shaolin|Shaolin Master Killer]]'', (Shao Lin san shi liu fang). Masta only appeared on one track on the Wu-Tang Clan's first album, in the closing verse to \"Da Mystery of Chessboxin\". Masta only narrowly made the track, and was almost left off in favor of [[Killah Priest]]. In fact, on the ''No Said Date'' DVD, Killah Priest claims that he and Masta Killa were in competition for the spot on \"Da Mystery of Chessboxin'\", and while Killah Priest fell asleep, Masta Killa stayed up all night writing and Killah Priest woke up the next morning to Masta Killa's verse. Since he was a developing rapper at the time ''[[Enter the Wu-Tang (36 Chambers)]]'' was being written, his verse in \"Da Mystery of Chessboxin\" was the only one that could hold up with the other, more experienced Wu-Tang members.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rapreviews.com/interview/mkilla06.html |title=RapReview Feature for October 3, 2006 \u2013 Masta Killa Interview |website=RapReviews.com |author=Adam Bernard  |date=October 3, 2006 |accessdate=April 4, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDuring the first round of solo projects, he made several appearances on tracks now considered Wu-Tang classics, such as \"Winter Warz\", \"Duel of the Iron Mic\", and \"Glaciers of Ice\". His flow at the time attracted attention for being very slow and laid-back, in contrast to the more manic, forceful styles of members like [[Inspectah Deck]] and [[Ghostface Killah]]. Masta Killa is also the Clansman fondest of [[China|Chinese]] [[martial art]]s imagery. In 1997, the Wu-Tang Clan's second album ''[[Wu-Tang Forever]]'' saw Masta become a mainstay in the group's line-up with regular appearances throughout the double album.\n\nMasta Killa was the last member to release a solo project, after it was delayed for several years and finally released in June 2004 with the title ''[[No Said Date]]''; critically acclaimed, it became independent label [[Nature Sounds]]' best-selling album, notable for featuring every core member of the Wu-Tang Clan on the album after a period in the group's history that lacked unity. His second album, ''[[Made in Brooklyn]]'', was released on August 8, 2006, and includes production from [[Pete Rock]] and [[MF Doom]]. \"Ringing Bells\", the [[Wu-Tang Clan affiliates#Bronze Nazareth|Bronze Nazareth]]-produced lead single from the album, was released in March 2006. Also in 2006, Masta Killa became the latest in a succession of hip hop artists to endorse [[PETA]], and participated in an advertisement for the organization to promote [[animal rights]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.contactmusic.net/wu-tang-clan/news/masta-killa-praised-for-being-animal-friendly_1057451 |title=Masta Killa Praised For Being Animal-friendly |website=contactmusic.net |date=January 25, 2008 |accessdate=March 6, 2017 |quote=I'll do anything that's going to save animals. Anytime I can encourage people to think twice before doing anything to animals that's a good thing.}}</ref> and a [[vegetarian]] lifestyle.<ref name=PETA>{{cite web |url=http://www.peta.org/videos/masta-killa-vegetarian-testimonial/ |title=Masta Killa: Vegetarian Testimonial |website=PETA.org |date= |author= |accessdate=June 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2012 he released his third album titled ''[[Selling My Soul]]'', an LP with heavy soul grooves and guests including [[Kurupt]] and the late [[Ol' Dirty Bastard]]. The album was intended as a precursor to his long-awaited album ''Loyalty is Royalty'', first announced in 2010 and eventually released in 2017.<ref name=SMS_announce>{{cite web |url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.21606/title.masta-killa-announces-new-album-selling-my-soul-due-december-11th |title=Masta Killa Announces New Album \"Selling My Soul,\" Due December 11th |website=HipHopDX |date=October 22, 2012 |author=Steven Horowitz |accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref><ref name=LIR_2010>{{cite web |url=http://hiphopdx.com/news/id.10865/title.masta-killa-preps-live-loyalty-is-royalty-soul-substance |title=Masta Killa Preps \"Live,\" \"Loyalty Is Royalty\" & \"Soul & Substance\" |website=HipHopDX |date=March 21, 2010 |author=Paul Arnold |accessdate=June 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn the Wu-Tang Corp. website, Masta Killa stated, \"I know I seem serious and quiet to a lot of the fans. That's because I take my work seriously. It's not a game. The Clan and I work hard to give you the best.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wutang-corp.com/artists/wu-artist.php?id=5 |title=Masta Killa Biography at Wu-Tang Corp. \u2013 The Official Site of the Wu-Tang Clan |website=Wu-Tang Corp. |date= |accessdate=April 24, 2014}}</ref> He is a fan of [[Gladys Knight]], [[Patti LaBelle]], [[Barry White]], [[Parliament-Funkadelic]] and [[Ohio Players]].<ref name=NobSm_Int_Pt2>{{cite web|url=http://www.nobodysmiling.com/hiphop/interview/86569.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060823040612/http://www.nobodysmiling.com/hiphop/interview/86569.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 23, 2006 |title=Masta Killa \u2013 Lion Heart Pt.2 \u2013 Interview |website=Nobody Smiling |date= |author=Michael Ivey |accessdate=June 24, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\nLike fellow Wu-Tang Clan members [[GZA]] and [[RZA]], Masta Killa is a [[vegetarian]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Reskin |first=Lauren |url=http://blogs.miaminewtimes.com/shortorder/2010/06/meatless_in_miami_vegetarians.php |title=Meatless in Miami: Vegetarians in Popular Song |website=Miami New Times |date=June 16, 2010 |accessdate=August 19, 2010}}</ref>\n\nMasta Killa is related to both [[Marvin Gaye]] and [[Nat Turner]], as revealed in the 2019 Wu-Tang documentary \u2018\u2019[[Of Mics and Men]]\u2019\u2019.\n\n==Moniker and aliases==\nMasta Killa gets his name from the 1978 kung fu movie ''[[Shaolin Master Killer]]'', also known as the ''[[36th Chamber of Shaolin]]''. He is often referred to as Jamel Irief.<ref name=NobSm_Int_Pt1>{{cite web|url=http://www.nobodysmiling.com/hiphop/interview/86565.php |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060813122804/http://www.nobodysmiling.com/hiphop/interview/86565.php |url-status=dead |archive-date=August 13, 2006 |title=Masta Killa \u2013 Lion Heart Pt.1 \u2013 Interview |website=Nobody Smiling |date= |author=Michael Ivey |accessdate=June 24, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Masta Killa discography}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n* ''[[No Said Date]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[Made in Brooklyn]]'' (2006)\n* ''[[Selling My Soul]]'' (2012)\n* ''[[Loyalty is Royalty]]'' (2017)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n* [http://www.myspace.com/mastakilla Masta Killa's Myspace]\n* [http://wutang-corp.com/artists/wu-artist.php?id=5 Masta Killa Biography]\n\n{{Masta Killa}}\n{{Wu-Tang Clan}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Masta Killa}}\n[[Category:African-American male rappers]]\n[[Category:Five percenters]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Wu-Tang Clan members]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n", "name_user": "2601:46:200:27f7:7436:d9d8:3a39:4ab0", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Masta_Killa"}
{"title_page": "Vachirawit Chiva-aree", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Thai actor, host, model and singer}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Vachirawit Chivaaree\n| image              = Bbrightvc.jpg\n| imagesize          = 250px\n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| native_name        = \u0e27\u0e0a\u0e34\u0e23\u0e27\u0e34\u0e0a\u0e0d\u0e4c \u0e0a\u0e35\u0e27\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e23\u0e35\n| native_name_lang   = tha\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1997|12|27}}\n| birth_place        = [[Nakhon Pathom]], Thailand\n| alma_mater         = \n| height             = {{height|ft=6|in=0.2}} <ref>{{cite web |title=Q&A\ud83d\ude35|url=https://www.instagram.com/stories/highlights/17847833104423976/ |website=instagram.com |publisher= @bbrightvc|accessdate=March 27, 2020 |language=Thai |date=September 2018}}</ref>\n| other_names        = Bright\n| occupation         = Actor, [[Talk show host|Host]], Model, Singer\n| years_active       = 2013\u2013present\n| notable_works      = {{plainlist|\n* '''Young Peng''' in  ''[[My Ambulance]]''\n* '''Sarawat''' in ''[[2gether: The Series (Thai TV series)|2gether: The Series]]''\n}}\n| agent              = [[GMMTV]]\n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Vachirawit Chivaaree''' ({{lang-th|\u0e27\u0e0a\u0e34\u0e23\u0e27\u0e34\u0e0a\u0e0d\u0e4c \u0e0a\u0e35\u0e27\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e23\u0e35}}; also known as '''Bright''' ({{lang-th|\u0e44\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e17}}), born December 27, 1997) is a Thai actor, singer, host and model. He is best known for his role as a ''Young Peng'' in the television series ''[[My Ambulance]]'' (2019) and as ''Sarawat'' in ''[[2gether: The Series (Thai TV series)|2gether: The Series]]'' (2020), where he stars as [[Metawin Opas-iamkajorn]]'s love interest.\n\n==Early life and education==\nVachirawit was born on December 27, 1997 in [[Nakhon Pathom Province]], Thailand.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0e1b\u0e23\u0e30\u0e27\u0e31\u0e15\u0e34 \"\u0e44\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e17 \u0e27\u0e0a\u0e34\u0e23\u0e27\u0e34\u0e0a\u0e0d\u0e4c\" \u0e17\u0e33\u0e04\u0e27\u0e32\u0e21\u0e23\u0e39\u0e49\u0e08\u0e31\u0e01\u0e19\u0e31\u0e01\u0e41\u0e2a\u0e14\u0e07\u0e14\u0e32\u0e27\u0e23\u0e38\u0e48\u0e07 \u0e2b\u0e19\u0e38\u0e48\u0e21\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22-\u0e2d\u0e40\u0e21\u0e23\u0e34\u0e01\u0e31\u0e19 \u0e08\u0e32\u0e01\u0e23\u0e31\u0e49\u0e27 \u0e21.\u0e01\u0e23\u0e38\u0e07\u0e40\u0e17\u0e1e |url=https://www.sanook.com/campus/1399611/ |website=sanook.com |publisher=Sanook |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |language=Thai |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> He completed his secondary education in [[Suankularb Wittayalai School]]. He took up Thammasat English Engineering Programme (TEPE) under the Faculty of Engineering of [[Thammasat University]]. He is currently taking up Marketing (International Program) in [[Bangkok University]].<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0e27\u0e0a\u0e34\u0e23\u0e27\u0e34\u0e0a\u0e0d\u0e4c \u0e0a\u0e35\u0e27\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e23\u0e35 (\u0e44\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e17\u0e4c) |url=https://www.nangdee.com/name/f/14724/\u0e44\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e17\u0e4c-\u0e27\u0e0a\u0e34\u0e23\u0e27\u0e34\u0e0a\u0e0d\u0e4c-\u0e0a\u0e35\u0e27\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e23\u0e35.html |website=nangdee.com |publisher=Nang Dee |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |language=Thai}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=9 Things You Need To Know About Bright Vachirawit |url=https://www.thaiupdate.info/bright-vachirawit-profile/ |website=thaiupdate.info |publisher=Thai Update |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe joined the entertainment industry as a TV show host for ''{{ill|Strawberry Krubcake|th|\u0e2a\u0e15\u0e23\u0e2d\u0e40\u0e1a\u0e2d\u0e23\u0e35\u0e48\u0e04\u0e23\u0e31\u0e1a\u0e40\u0e04\u0e49\u0e01}}'' on [[Channel 3 (Thailand)|Channel 3]]. He became part of the music video ''Gawt Mai Dai'' by Bedroom Audio. In 2016, he debuted as an actor in the movie ''Love Say Hey''<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0e40\u0e25\u0e34\u0e1f\u0e40\u0e0b\u0e40\u0e2e.. \u0e2d\u0e22\u0e32\u0e01\u0e40\u0e0b\u0e27\u0e48\u0e32\u0e23\u0e31\u0e01\u0e40\u0e18\u0e2d (2016) |url=https://www.nangdee.com/title/html/4430/\u0e40\u0e25\u0e34\u0e1f\u0e40\u0e0b\u0e40\u0e2e..-\u0e2d\u0e22\u0e32\u0e01\u0e40\u0e0b\u0e27\u0e48\u0e32\u0e23\u0e31\u0e01\u0e40\u0e18\u0e2d.html |website=nangdee.com |publisher=Nang Dee |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |language=Thai}}</ref> and starred in the TV series ''I Sea U'' as ''Peter'' along with [[Ungsumalynn Sirapatsakmetha]] (Pattie) and [[:th:\u0e40\u0e21\u0e06 \u0e40\u0e21\u0e06\u0e27\u0e31\u0e12\u0e19\u0e32|Mek Mekwattana]] (Jessie).<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0e41\u0e0b\u0e48\u0e1a\u0e09\u0e38\u0e14\u0e2b\u0e31\u0e27\u0e43\u0e08! \"\u0e44\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e17-\u0e27\u0e0a\u0e34\u0e23\u0e27\u0e34\u0e0a\u0e0d\u0e4c \u0e0a\u0e35\u0e27\u0e2d\u0e32\u0e23\u0e35\" \u0e2b\u0e19\u0e38\u0e48\u0e21\u0e2b\u0e25\u0e48\u0e2d\u0e25\u0e39\u0e01\u0e04\u0e23\u0e36\u0e48\u0e07\u0e44\u0e17\u0e22-\u0e2d\u0e40\u0e21\u0e23\u0e34\u0e01\u0e31\u0e19 |url=https://praew.com/people/274469.html |website=praew.com |publisher=Praew |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |language=Thai |date=September 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe is currently one of the hosts of ''Toelaew'', a [[GMM 25]] program and plays the role of ''Sarawat'' in ''[[2gether: The Series (Thai TV series)|2gether: The Series]]'' where he is being paired with [[Metawin Opas-iamkajorn]] (Win).<ref name=\"releasedate\">{{cite web |title=#\u0e04\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19\u0e01\u0e39 \"\u0e40\u0e1e\u0e23\u0e32\u0e30\u0e40\u0e23\u0e32\u0e04\u0e39\u0e48\u0e01\u0e31\u0e19 2gether The Series\" \u0e40\u0e1b\u0e47\u0e19\u0e01\u0e23\u0e30\u0e41\u0e2a \u0e15\u0e31\u0e49\u0e07\u0e41\u0e15\u0e48\u0e17\u0e35\u0e40\u0e0b\u0e2d\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e25\u0e48\u0e32\u0e2a\u0e38\u0e14 \u0e04\u0e31\u0e48\u0e19\u0e01\u0e39 EP1 \u0e23\u0e2d\u0e14\u0e39 \u0e44\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e17\u0e27\u0e34\u0e19 #\u0e2a\u0e32\u0e23\u0e27\u0e31\u0e15\u0e23 #\u0e44\u0e17\u0e19\u0e4c\u0e04\u0e19\u0e0a\u0e34\u0e04 |url=https://medhubnews.com/\u0e14\u0e39\u0e1a\u0e17\u0e04\u0e27\u